antsfield, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tunstall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tūn-stall</i> ‘site of a farm, farmstead’, notably Tunstall (Lancashire) and one or more of many Staffordshire places (Tunstall near Stoke on Trent, Tunstall near Adbaston, and four places called Dunstall), but also Tunstall Farm in Mountfield (Sussex) and possibly also Tunstall (Durham, Kent, Norfolk, Shropshire, Suffolk, east and North Yorkshire), and Dunstall (Lincolnshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tunstill","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Tunstall  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Tunstall I was born about 1161, in Tunstall, Lancashire, England. He had at least 3 sons with Maud Tunstall. He died about 1203, in Cantsfield, Lancashire, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"about 1161–about 1203":"umbes 1161–umbes 1203","1166–Female":"1166–Surnud","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1183–1246":"1183–1246","1205–1246":"1205–1246","1161–1203":"1161–1203","about 1161":"umbes 1161","about 1183":"umbes 1183","1205":"1205","about 1181":"umbes 1181","1203":"1203","1246":"1246","1166":"1166","about 1203":"umbes 1203","1161":"1161","1183":"1183","1181":"1181","Tunstall, Lancashire, England":"Tunstall, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Cantsfield, Lancashire, England":"Cantsfield, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1161–about 1203":"noin 1161–noin 1203","1166–Female":"1166–Kuollut","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1183–1246":"1183–1246","1205–1246":"1205–1246","1161–1203":"1161–1203","about 1161":"noin 1161","about 1183":"noin 1183","1205":"1205","about 1181":"noin 1181","1203":"1203","1246":"1246","1166":"1166","about 1203":"noin 1203","1161":"1161","1183":"1183","1181":"1181","Tunstall, Lancashire, England":"Tunstall, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Cantsfield, Lancashire, England":"Cantsfield, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1161–about 1203":"environ 1161–environ 1203","1166–Female":"1166–Décédée","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1183–1246":"1183–1246","1205–1246":"1205–1246","1161–1203":"1161–1203","about 1161":"environ 1161","about 1183":"environ 1183","1205":"1205","about 1181":"environ 1181","1203":"1203","1246":"1246","1166":"1166","about 1203":"environ 1203","1161":"1161","1183":"1183","1181":"1181","Tunstall, Lancashire, England":"Tunstall, Lancashire,